text.tspan: precise calculations:General Arrangement PlanCapacity Plan with Deadweight scale Midship Section Plan Lines Plan Shell Expansion Plan Docking Plan Trim and Stability booklet or hydrostatic information ( summer loaded figures at zero trim for extreme draft, displacement, deadweight and tons of immersion)Please specify in the subject of the message, the vessel`s current name, IMO Number and if available, the vessel`s SIN ( PanamaCanal Ship Identification Number)The above mentioned documentation shall be submitted to 96 hours prior to arrival at Panama Canal Waters.This information in advance will allow in expediting the vessel`s scheduling process, the calculations required for the properassessment of tolls, and facilitate the inspection process on arrival.This advance information will minimize the possibility that transit might be denied due tononcompliance with Canal regulations.Note: All vessels transiting the Panama Canal are required to have on deck 6 manila or synthetic mooring lines forward and aft (Total12) prior commencement of transit. These lines should be atleast 75 Mtrs long with an eye of at least 1.50 mtrs long spliced in oneend, there is no specification on the diameter of the line and hence a mooring rope appropriate for the size of the vessel is adequate.A rope of at least 150 mtrs length with an eye at either end qualifies as two lines for the purpose of this requirement and hence a totalof 6 mooring ropes with eyes at either end will suffice.9.4.6SUEZ CANAL TRANSITDocuments to be produced for Suez Transit in due time are:Suez Canal Special Tonnage Certificate and Calculation Sheets (3 copies in the first transit).Certificate of Registry and ship's drawing.3 copies of Suez Canal certificate3 copies of GA plan3 copies of capacity plan3 copies of engine room planStatistical Declaration.Extract from the vessel's official documents and information concerning the vessel's type and her cargo.Declaration concerning the use of double bottom tanks and the lower parts of the high tanks.Declaration concerning vessels in ballast.Declaration of State of Navigability.The last Classification Certificate issued.Any other information necessary for transiting the Canal.(I.O.P.P.) International Oil Pollution Prevention Certificate of Compliance and its supplement for the record of construction andequipment.10COMMUNICATIONPrompt and Effective communications between the Vessel and Office, Agents, and Charterers are vital for efficient operations.Procedures to be followed by the vessel are given in Section 4.0 of Vessel Operations Manual.10.1INTERNAL COMMUNICATIONThe company believes that effective communication will help motivate staff, define and verify roles and procedures, monitormanagement systems performance, and act to identify potential for improvement.Communications require Top – to – Bottom as well as Bottom – to – Top flow of information and that employee suggestions areextremely effective in improving procedures and products.The Company shall consult with its employees (Ship / Shore staff) regarding pertinent OH&S information. Such information shall besent out to ships and their feedback sought on these issues.Processes have been established within the organisation for internal communication on environmentally related matters including theireffectiveness.A.
